BOC John:<br><br>
I remember being placed among the expectants at a MASH hospital.  I wasn't placed there because I was expected to die like they were.. but because I had a broken back and could wait an indefinite period.. while all available resources where being directed to saving those who had a chance.  It was an erie feeling.. I believe that many of them were already dead or unconscious... quite a few were moaning or screaming and a few were verbal.  They were asking for God to save them or in most cases they were calling out for loved ones...Moms ..wives.. children..etc.<br>
It is tragic that their messages died with them... just faded away in the humid tropic air... but they are etched in my mind forever!  I lay there for several hours waiting treatment for my non life threatening injury and watched the last of them die.  Some died quietly, others thrashed about and twitched.. some simply cried.  Mom and Jesus were the two most spoken words.<br><br>
I applaud you for your suggestion of a gift of fond memories to those who lost someone special.  I am afraid that I will not be able to help you... I'm just too weak!  But I will pray for you and your success in giving something back!<br><br>
You're a Good Man John - and you're my BRO.<br><br>
MTF
